08329nam a22009615i 9783110580082DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105800827 a10.1515/97831105800822doi  a(DE-B1597)490070  a(OCoLC)1049627508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a700.10300aDisruption in the Arts :bTextual, Visual, and Performative Strategies for Analyzing Societal Self-Descriptions /ced. by Lars Koch, Tobias Nanz, Johannes Pause. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (XV, 381 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture & Conflict ,x2194-7104 ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tDisruption in the Arts: Prologue -- tI. Conceptual Approaches -- tAesthetic experiments: On the Event-Like Character and the Function of Disruptions in the Arts -- tScandalous Expectations: Second Order Scandals in Modern Society -- tEkstasis and Paradoxa. The Miracle as Disruption -- tImagined Scenarios of Disruption. A Concept -- tII. Media -- tDisruptive Storytelling. Notes on E.T.A. Hoffmann -- tPerturbing the Reader: The Riddle-character of Art and the Dialectical Impact of Contemporary Literature (Adorno, Goetz, Kracht) -- tExpansions of the Instant: Disruptions of Time in Contemporary German Literature -- tDisruption, Photography, and the Idea of Aesthetic Resistance -- tIII. Body -- tInterferences: Posthuman Perspectives on Early Electronic Music -- tThe Dis/rupture of Film as Skin: Jean-Luc Nancy, Claire Denis, and Trouble Every Day -- t"They Starve to death, but who dares ask why?": Steve McQueen's Film Hunger -- tWriting Aphasia: Intermedial Observation of Disrupted Language in Wolfgang Herrndorf's Arbeit und Struktur -- tIV. Power -- tThe Red Telephone: A Hybrid Object of the Cold War -- tChristoph Schlingensief's Image Disruption Machine -- tCitizen n-1: Laura Poitras's Citizenfour as a Reparative Reading of a Paranoid World -- tV. Archive -- tNotes on Secondary Drama -- tDisturbance in the Intermediate: Secondary Drama as a Parasite -- tSignal-to-Noise Ratio -- tDisrupted Arts and Marginalized Humans: A Commentary on Friedrich Kittler's "Signal-to-Noise Ratio" -- tContributors -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Persons0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe volume examines from a comparative perspective the phenomenon of aesthetic disruption within the various arts in contemporary culture. It assumes that the political potential of contemporary art is not solely derived from presenting its audiences with openly political content, but rather from creating a space of perception and interaction using formal means: a space that makes hegemonic structures of action and communication observable, thus problematizing their self-evidence. The contributions conceptualize historical and contemporary politics of form in the media, which aim to be more than mere shock strategies, which are concerned not just with the 'narcissistic' exhibition of art as art, but also with the creation of a new common horizon of experience. They combine the analysis of paradigmatic works, procedures and actions with reference to theoretical debates in the fields of literature, media and art of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. The essay-collection shows how textual, visual, auditive or performative strategies disclose their own ways of functioning, intervene in automated processes of reception and thus work on stimulating a sense of political possibilities. The editors acknowledge support from the European Union's Seventh Framework Program (FP 7/ 2007-2013), ERC grant agreement no. 312454.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by European Research Council (ERC)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps:/